ng and its implications for class relations.Anyone interested in labor history, women's history, and the sociology of work or gender will want to read this pathbreaking book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aGender Studies. 4aLabor History. 4aU.S. History.1 aBaron, Ava, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171124440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501711244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501711244/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles